Attendance Is

Compulsory For
Male Students

By IRWIN ROSEN
Representatives of the Army,
Navy, and Marines will be on hand
at the University today to explain
details, to answer questions, to
give information, to all students in-
terested in the various reserve

‘ COI‘pS programs.

- The three service officers will be

‘heard ﬁrst at an assembly of all

male undergraduate students at
Soldiers’ and Sailors’ Memorial
auditorium this morning at 10:30
o’clock.
Attendance is required of all
male students who will be excus-
‘ ed from third hour classes and
who will be granted excuses for
late entrance into fourth hour
classes, should the meeting run
over one hour.
Classes will be conducted as
, usual for all women, according to
‘ Dean of Women Helen Rush.
After students have heard the

V ‘officers at the assembly, they will

be given an opportunity to confer
with them individually this after-
noon when the men will be station-
ed at different rooms on the second
ﬂoor of the Cathedral of Learning.
From 1:15 untl 3:30 o'clock

the Army representative will be
-in 216, the Army Air Force rep-
resentative in 221, the Navy rep-
resentative in 226, (for those in-
terested in V-1 and V-7) and in

230 for those interested in the

V-5 program, and the Marine rep-

resentative will interview stu-

dents in room 249.

V-1 members are considered ap-
prentice seamen in the naval re-
serve, and after completion of one
year’s work at the University they
will be transferred into either V-5
or V-7.

V-5 is the naval aviation reserve

program. Those who elect V-5 will .
be permitted to ﬁnish the second

calendar year of university work
and then they will be transferred
to the Navy for training as officer
pilots.

Those who elect V-7 will be per-
mitted to remain at the University
until they have completed work for
degrees. Then they will go into the
Navy training course preparatory
to receiving ensign’s commissions.

It is well to bear these basic
differences between the Navy’s

“V” programs in mind before ap-

plying for any of them.

The University conference this
morning is part of a nation wide

tour _of all universities and col-

leges to make further known to

students opportunities in the en-
listed reserve corps programs
that are open to them.

No one is to enlist in any reserve
corps today, it was stressed by
Lawrence R. Irwin, service co-ordi-
nator. Today’s sessions are only to
clear up any confusion about the
various reserve corps programs
that students may have. The offi-
cers will be back on campus in a few
weeks. It is at this time that stu-
dents who are interested should
enlist.

