Go-and Bring Your Questions

This morning’s appearance of
members of the Army, the Navy,
and the Marines to explain and to
clear up questions on the various
enlisted reserve programs marks
the most signiﬁcant attempt yet
taken by the government to clear
up the confusion that has thus far
marked all the reserve corps plans.

When will the reserve corps
members he called? What are his
chances for graduation, even un-
der the accelerated program?

What about the scholastic and

physical requirements? What is

the attitude of the Army and the

Navy towards men already en-

rolled in college?——all this we

want to know.

And about all these things we’ve
heard wild rumors, garbled press
reports, denials that sounded too
much like high—pressure business
talks from educational leaders.

Now at last we’re going to get
the truth. It is the patriotic duty of
every male student to not only at-
tend these meetings and talk with
the service representatives——-but to
ask questions, frankly, fearlessly,
and intelligently.

Questions like the ones we’ve
raised above. Questions that

‘ each individual student may have

on his mind. Because these men
ARE the Army, the Navy, and
the Marines—and it is only
through hearing from us, the
students, that they can explain
and make known their reserve
plans with less muddling and con-
fusion on the part of all con-
cerned.

